<li class="collection__item">
<h2 class="title">Joseph Haydn (1732-1809)</h2>
<p class="paragraph-text">Going back to the <a href="/discover-music/periods-genres/classical/">Classical</a> era, and <a href="/composers/haydn/">Haydn</a> is the first of the trio of composers that get called the <a href="/discover-music/first-viennese-school-classical/">Viennese School</a>  alongside <a href="/composers/mozart/">Mozart</a> and <a href="/composers/beethoven/">Beethoven</a>. </p><p class="paragraph-text">The Austrian composer was the son of a steelmaker, and went on to become the father of the symphony  he wrote 107 of them, alongside the 83 string quartets, 45 piano trios, 62 piano sonatas, 14 masses and 26 operas, all that define the formal Classical style of Vienna.   </p><p class="paragraph-text"><strong>Read more: </strong><a href="/discover-music/first-viennese-school-classical/"><strong>What is the Viennese School, and why do classical people say it?</strong></a></p>
